The eldrazi have two problems. 1. from a storyline perspective they've been ruined. Seeing hints of them in the first two Zendikar blocks and then having them explode in Rise made for a fantastic bit of Lovecraftian storytelling. They were this crazy powerful mysterious eldrich force that seemed to be consuming an entire plane with zero hope of stopping them. That's great. Battle and Shadows shit all over that by making them common and mundane. They are the spice that make soup delicious when you add a pinch, and ruins it when you dump in the whole container. And Battle and Shadows dumped in three containers. They ceased to be this distant, barely glimpsed horror and became pedestrian both due to their commonality and due to the fact that the storyline utterly neutered them as a threat. That parallel extended to the game too where they went from this thing you saw occasionally so this thing that felt like was in every deck. Not that I ever wanted to see some gross annihilator beast, but it became -boring- to see eldrazi.

2. They're too generically useful by being colorless. There's almost no situation where a big ass annihilating permanent-destroying colorless threat that Elixir of Immortalities your graveyard when killed isn't useful. It's like someone dared WotC to find something more eye-rolling than the dude who jams Terestadon in every green deck. "We'll let you jam a colorless Terestadon into every deck period!".
I completely agree. And folks who respond with “But they cost 10/11 mana!” every mono-green deck just says “Hold my beer...”.
